questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput Java 21 application was recently migrated to use `Virtual Threads` to handle I/O-bound requests. However, monitoring shows that the application is experiencing significant latency spikes and CPU saturation. You find the following code snippet in a shared logging utility: 

java
public class LogService {
    public synchronized void logTransaction(String data) {
        // Simulate writing to a slow remote syslog server
        remoteLogger.send(data);
    }
}

Multiple `Virtual Threads` call this `logTransaction` method simultaneously.

You are debugging a production issue where a Spring Boot service is failing to roll back database transactions. The service uses a `CompletableFuture` to perform parallel processing of order items. The code looks like this:

java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Autowired private OrderRepository repository;

    @Transactional
    public CompletableFuture<Void> processOrder(Order order) {
        return CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> {
            repository.save(order);
            if (order.getAmount() < 0) throw new RuntimeException("Invalid amount");
        });
    }
}

Even when an exception is thrown, the order remains saved in the database.

You are debugging a production issue where a system utilizing a complex chain of `CompletableFuture` tasks is intermittently hanging. Thread dumps reveal that many threads are in a `WAITING` state, but the `ForkJoinPool.commonPool()` shows high contention. The code involves a pattern where a parent `CompletableFuture` waits for several child futures created within its own execution block using `join()`:

java
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    var f1 = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> serviceA.call());
    var f2 = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> serviceB.call());
    return f1.join() + f2.join(); // Internal waiting
});
